706136f-d.text:
Orange Street, north side, between Henry and Hicks Streets, showing the Plymouth Church, from which the well-known Brooklyn preacher Henry Ward Beecher delivered his sermons. The church was built in 1849 and a brass plate on one of the pews indicates where Abrsham Lincoln, friend of the minister, sat to henr his sermons. The edifice extends through to Cranberry Street, one block to the north, and views of that side of the building can be found in the Cranberry Street file. The views (except 3) are east from Hicks
Street.
For additional data see "The New York Times," October 5, 1940.
Views 1,2,3:  1925
Eugene L. Armbruster
View 4:  June 11, 1927
P. L. Sperr

706142f-a.text:
74.78 Orange Street, south side, west of Henry Street. The home at the left,No. 78,was occupied by Dr. Morrell of Plymouth Church, and later by bt. U.M. Smith. The home on the right, No. 72,was occupied by the Hon.
Moses F. O'Dell, a member of Congress.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
